{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652358"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:35:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:35:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18533"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18533"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76766"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11265"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18533"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62261"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10711"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26131"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76766"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring a genetics consultation, a diagram is shown depicting a chromosomal rearrangement. The diagram illustrates the fusion of two acrocentric chromosomes at their centromeres, resulting in the formation of a single metacentric chromosome.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this type of chromosomal rearrangement?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Robertsonian translocation","Reciprocal translocation","Pericentric inversion","Paracentric inversion","Isochromosome formation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChromosomes can be classified by centromere position as metacentric (central), submetacentric (slightly off-centre), or acrocentric (near one end). Human chromosomes 13, 14, 15, 21, and 22 are acrocentric.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagram described in the stem shows a \u003Cstrong\u003ERobertsonian translocation\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterised by the fusion of two acrocentric chromosomes at their centromeres. During this process, the short arms are lost, but since these contain only redundant ribosomal RNA genes, there is no significant clinical impact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther chromosomal rearrangements differ in their mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReciprocal translocation\u003C/strong\u003E involves the exchange of chromosome segments between two different non-homologous chromosomes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericentric inversion\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when a chromosome segment including the centromere breaks, rotates 180 degrees, and reattaches\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacentric inversion\u003C/strong\u003E involves the rotation of a chromosome segment within a single arm, not involving the centromere\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsochromosome formation\u003C/strong\u003E results from a transverse rather than longitudinal division of the centromere, creating a chromosome with identical arms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile carriers of Robertsonian translocations have a total of 45 chromosomes instead of the typical 46, they usually have no physical abnormalities. However, they may face fertility challenges and have an increased risk of producing offspring with chromosomal abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Robertsonian translocations occur when two acrocentric chromosomes (13, 14, 15, 21, 22) fuse at their centromeres.","In Robertsonian translocations, the short arms of the involved chromosomes are lost but this does not cause significant clinical effects.","Carriers of Robertsonian translocations have 45 chromosomes but are phenotypically normal."],"references":["Lu W, Zhou J, Rao H, Yuan H, Huang S, Liu Y, Yang B. A Retrospective Analysis of Robertsonian Translocations from a Single Center in China. Reprod Sci. 2024 Mar;31(3):851-856. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10912152/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62261"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18533"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62261"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T11:15:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T11:15:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11265"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76766"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synon